sting
an event in New York in early March to launch the TWL x BR collaboration.) =
Then there were all the Gucci synergies, as Lauren noted ( https://puck.new=
s/guccis-white-lotus-invasion-and-the-saks-payment-sitch/?utm_campaign=3DLi=
ne+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F21%2F25%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRI=
BERS+%282%2F21%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&u=
tm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) earlier this week. Also, Tombolo did the hot=
el staff uniforms. The integrations are truly endless in a Barbie movie sor=
t of way. Remember that Gap Inc. C.E.O. Richard Dickson, who was a
Mattel exec at the time of the Barbie frenzy, takes credit for its dozens u=
pon dozens of partnerships.

Clearly, there=E2=80=99s a good deal of irony in the fact that this particu=
lar show, which skewers luxury consumption and excess, is participating so =
enthusiastically in creating more merchandise. On the other hand, whatever =
it skewers=E2=80=A6 it=E2=80=99s a business.

=E2=80=8A

The
Week in Feedback=E2=80=A6
-------------------

On the end of the downtown Dallas Neiman Marcus: =E2=80=9CAs a Dallas nativ=
e who still subscribes to
The Dallas Morning News, I am catatonic over the store closure. TBH, the st=
ore wasn=E2=80=99t that great. Didn=E2=80=99t carry all the designers. And =
frankly, no one in Dallas likes going to downtown downtown. It has no charm=
=2E But doing lunch during Christmastim=
e at the Zodiac Room was something man=
y of us grew up with. And all of that going away just hurts.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=94A strategy guy

On Neiman=E2=80=99s Dallas, but also on Catherine Bloom departing for Nords=
trom:
=E2=80=9CWhen I read =E2=80=98A Neiman Marcus Tragedy,=E2=80=99 I thought y=
ou were referring to their loss of Catherine Bloom to Nordstrom. While the =
closing of the NM downtown store is sad, the reality is that it had not bee=
n profitable for years. Dallas ladies simply will not go downtown, no matte=
r how much money Tim Headington spends trying to revitalize it, especially =
when Highland Park Village exists. ... Meanwhile, Catherine was a powerhous=
e revenue generator for NM Beverly. Her
defection is tragic for NM in my book.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94A former retail ex=
ec

Yes, more on Neiman=E2=80=99s Dallas: =E2=80=9CFor those mourning the loss =
of the Dallas Neiman Marcus, it was the subject of a documentary by Frederi=
ck Wiseman, called simply The Store. It includes lines such as, =E2=80=98Re=
member, every day here, you=E2=80=99re selling. Everything you do, every in=
teraction you have, every breath you take, needs to be in the service of se=
lling. But it shouldn=E2=80=99t
look like that. We=E2=80=99re not that kind of store. Our customers don=E2=
=80=99t appreciate being sold to.=E2=80=99 It screens ( https://www.filmlin=
c.org/films/the-store/?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F21%2F=
25%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F21%2F25%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) to=
night at Lincoln Center as part of a Wiseman retrospective. Would love to s=
ee someone film the tail end of the store=E2=80=99s life.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=94A documentary filmmaker

On the price-value equation: =E2=80=9CAs someone who buys a lot of The Row =
and many other brands (now
and historically), I=E2=80=99m confused by the relentless narrative that Th=
e Row is so expensive. Yes, it=E2=80=99s certainly not affordable to most, =
but it=E2=80=99s comparable to Louis Vuitton, Prada, Gucci, YSL, and yet be=
tter quality than all those brands. It=E2=80=99s less expensive than Botteg=
a, Loro Piana, Chanel, and Herm=C3=A8s, but just as well made, if not bette=
r. I wonder if some people just like to shit on The Row because it=E2=80=99=
s not a heritage European house but a =E2=80=98celebrity=E2=80=99 brand.=E2=
=80=9D =E2=80=94A designer

=E2=80=8A

Have a great weekend,
Lauren

