ts.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94<em>A strategy guy</em><br/><br/><em>On Neiman=E2=80=
=99s Dallas, but also on Catherine Bloom departing for Nordstrom</em>:
=E2=80=9CWhen I read =E2=80=98A Neiman Marcus Tragedy,=E2=80=99 I thought y=
ou were referring to their loss of <strong>Catherine Bloom</strong> to Nord=
strom. While the closing of the NM downtown store is sad, the reality is th=
at it had not been profitable for years. Dallas ladies simply will not go d=
owntown, no matter how much money <strong>Tim Headington</strong> spends tr=
ying to revitalize it, especially when Highland Park Village exists. ... Me=
anwhile, Catherine was a powerhouse revenue generator for NM Beverly. Her
defection is tragic for NM in my book.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94<em>A former retai=
l exec</em><br/><br/><em>Yes, more on Neiman=E2=80=99s Dallas</em>: =E2=80=
=9CFor those mourning the loss of the Dallas Neiman Marcus, it was the subj=
ect of a documentary by <strong>Frederick Wiseman</strong>, called simply <=
em>The Store</em>. It includes lines such as, =E2=80=98Remember, every day =
here, you=E2=80=99re selling. Everything you do, every interaction you have=
